article.description:
Freshman Barbara Turner and 
Diana Taurasi scored 17 points apiece as second-ranked
Connecticut cruised to an 82-48 rout of St. Joseph's.
article.headline: UConn bench outscores St. Joseph's reserves 37-6
article.linkText: UConn rolls to 48th straight win, routs  St. Joseph's
article.story:
HARTFORD, Conn.-- Connecticut's players wanted to head off
to vacation on a good note. They sure did.

	   Diana Taurasi and freshman Barbara Turner scored 17 points
apiece to lead the Huskies  (No. 2 ESPN/USA Today, No. 3 AP) past St. Joseph's 82-48 Sunday for
their 48th straight victory.

	   "We had a lot of energy coming out," Turner said. "We wanted
to have a good game before we went home."

	   The 6-foot swing player from Cleveland is one of four top
recruits UConn landed to replace last season's All-American
starters Sue Bird, Swin Cash, Tamika Williams and Asjha Jones.

	   Turner provided speed on the break Sunday and was able to finish
from the baseline or draw the foul trying. She made all five of her
free throws.

	   "She's got confidence right now. She's a heck of a shooter,"
UConn coach Geno Auriemma said. "She's a good post player for a
kid her size. Barbara's got a lot to offer right now."

	   Turner set a career best in scoring and tied her best for
rebounds, eight. The Huskies (9-0) outscored the Hawks 32-16 in the
paint. Ashley Battle led the national champions with 11 rebounds.

	   The Hawks (3-5) are 0-3 against ranked teams season, after also
losing to top-ranked Duke and Penn State.

	   Taurasi had a dozen points in the first half and helped stake
Connecticut to a 14-0 lead about six minutes in, as the Hawks
missed their first eight shots.

	   Irina Krasnoshiok ended the drought with a jumper in the lane,
and St. Joseph's hit six of its next seven shots to draw within
five midway through the first half. They never got closer.

	   "I think our kids competed for close to about 20-to-25 minutes
and they wouldn't give way, which is a good sign," St. Joseph's
coach Cindy Griffin said.

	   Turner, a reserve, scored six in an 8-2 run to put UConn up
28-17. The Huskies led 37-21 at halftime.

	   UConn center Jessica Moore hit two quick inside baskets to open
the second half, and the Huskies shot 60 percent over the final 20
minutes. Turner capped a 17-9 with a backdoor layup for a 54-30
lead with 14 minutes left.

	   Taurasi, who added seven assists and three blocks, picked up her
fourth foul a few minutes later and left the game, but by then
UConn's reserves had the game in hand.

	   UConn's bench outscored St. Joseph's reserves 37-6.

	   Krasnoshiok led the Hawks with 12 points. She and Stephanie
Graff each had eight rebounds.

	   After its break is over, UConn travels to games at South Florida
and Florida State, then it takes on No. 4 Tennessee in two weeks.

	   "Connecticut is going to be a work in progress," Griffin said.
"They are young kids. They are going to get better as the season
progresses. No doubt about it."
